default2.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultTo what extent are the needs of different groups of passengers (e.g. people with disabilities, older people, young people) take
defaultn into account in determining the provision of public transport to isolated communities?
default&#xa0;
default2.2.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAccount taken of different groups’ requirement
defaults
default is patchy
default:
default  
defaultIt is the experience of the CTA and the CT sector that the account taken of different groups’ needs can va
defaultry widely by area.  Typically this can depend on the structure of the local authority transport department or even on the commitment of a small team or one individual.
default&#xa0;
default2.2.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultL
defaultack of network planning 
defaultdu
defaulte to the unregulated 
defaultbus 
defaultmarket
default:
default  
defaultThere is a lack of ability
default to develop planned public transport networks outside London due to the de-regulated nature of the market.  This, in turn, means that it can be difficult for local authorities to influence the extent to which services take account of different passenger gr
defaultoups in isolated areas.  The current economic climate also means that authorities are less able to support socially necessary bus services
default through tendered routes.
default&#xa0;
default2.2.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultDisadvantaged groups
default’
default needs are often an afterthought
default:
default  
defaultIt is understandable that transport authorities and operators seek to maximise the efficiency of the services they procure and/or operate.  Too often, however, the needs of marginalised groups of people are not fully considered
default from the outset
default.  One clear 
defaultexample of this is the failure to require the mandatory reimbursement 
defaultfor transportation 
defaultof eligible concessionary pass holders on services 
default(such as community transport) 
defaultwhere no registered local bus service operates or where such services are inaccessible
default 
defaultto users.
default  The transport of young people is 
defaultalso a particular 
defaultissue as no consistent concessionary arrangement exists for them across 
defaultEngland.  A national 
defaultyoung persons’ 
defaultconcession would not only help to address the problems of isolation for young people,
default it would also help to build the habit at an early age of using public/community transport rather than assuming obtaining a car is the solution to all transport problems.
default&#xa0;
default2.2.4
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultExpectation that CT will pick up needs that others cannot meet:
default  
defaultIn recent years we 
defaulthave seen 
defaulta
default 
defaultgrowing assumption that CT 
defaultservices will grow to fill the gaps 
defaultthat commercial/statutory providers are unable to.  However, this increasing demand for CT services is set against a backdrop of decreasing funding which is stretching 
defaultmany to break
defaulting point.  Many CT
default operators have sought to develop a social enterprise business model in order to become more sustainable.  This has been successful for some but has 
defaultalso resulted in some struggling to manage new business relationships, particularly when
default service commissioners do not appear prepared to pay for the full cost of the service received
default.
default  
defaultThere is 
defaultonly 
defaultlimited use of community audit or transport needs 
defaultanalysis 
defaultat 
defaultd
defaultistrict or 
defaultparish level, which could 
defaultpotentially 
defaultbetter inform authorities of user
default needs.
