default2.3.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultLack of integrated network planning
default:
default  
defaultThe inability to plan and develop an integrated network is a challenge for 
defaulttransport 
defaultauthorities. The l
defaultack of bus
default route/market
default regulation
default which would allow this means that only profitable routes are developed in many areas.
default  This leads to an expectation th
defaultat transport authorities and/or the CT sector will pick up on the needs of those who cannot access commercial bu
defaults
default services.
default&#xa0;
default2.3.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSilo funding mentality
default:
default  
defaultL
defaultocal authorities, 
defaulthealth 
defaultagencies, government departments and other bodies 
defaultappear to be
default 
defaulttrying to protect
default 
defaulttheir 
defaultown budgets rather than 
defaultfocusing on the strategic benefits of 
defaultintegrate
defaultd
default services.
default 
defaultThe complex nature of the NHS and its particular transport requirements is a significant challenge in this respect.  There is evidence of the NHS 
defaultreducing 
defaulttransport p
defaultrovision 
defaultin some areas 
defaultby changing (tightening) eligibility criteria in order to reduce transport spend.  This merely has the effect of requiring someone else (typically CT or local authorities) to deliver the transport.  It is not unusual for the CT secto
defaultr to deliver transport to health because the NHS will not or cannot pay for it.  
defaultIn many cases 
defaultthe charitable/voluntary sector is 
defaultnot receiving full cost recovery for services provided and so 
defaultit 
defaultis, in effect, 
defaultsubsidising 
defaultthe 
defaultstatutory
default sector (eg the NHS)
default.
